2026-06-15 | Delete the Middle Node of a Linked List

	Question
Delete the middle node and return the head.
	Key Insight
We need to find the middle node efficiently.
Use:
		slow pointer
		fast pointer
When:
		fast moves 2 steps
		slow moves 1 step
By the time fast reaches the end:
		slow points to the middle node.
To delete it, we also keep track of:
		prev = node before slow
Then:
		prev->next = slow->next
	Approach
1.	If the list contains only one node:
			return nullptr.
2.	Initialize:
			slow = head
			fast = head
			prev = nullptr
3.	Move:
			slow by 1 step
			fast by 2 steps
4.	When traversal ends:
			slow = middle node
5.	Delete the middle node:
			prev->next = slow->next
6.	Return head.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* deleteMiddle(ListNode* head) {
        if(head == nullptr || head->next == nullptr)
            return nullptr;
        ListNode* slow = head;
        ListNode* fast = head;
        ListNode* prev = nullptr;
        while(fast && fast->next) {
            prev = slow;
            slow = slow->next;
            fast = fast->next->next;
        }
        prev->next = slow->next;
        delete slow;
        return head;
    }
};
	Key Insight
The slow-fast pointer technique finds the middle node in a single traversal. Keeping a pointer to the node before the middle allows us to remove the middle node in O(1) time once it is found, giving an overall O(n) solution.
